As far as I can tell, we still write that field when used as designed.

```java
  static void addSearchFields(Span span, JsonGenerator writer) throws IOException {
    long timestampMillis = span.timestampAsLong() / 1000L;
    if (timestampMillis != 0L) writer.writeNumberField("timestamp_millis", timestampMillis);
```

To answer you directly, our storage implementations are considered internal (ElasticsearchSpanConsumer being package private double-downs on this). Among many things, this allows us to upgrade libraries whenever we need to.

Anyone using the storage (or collector) libraries directly should watch for drift, in other words. The only library with compatibility guarantees is the core library.

